04506nam a22005895i 9780822396680DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223966807 a10.1515/97808223966802doi  a(DE-B1597)552067  a(OCoLC)1229161636  a(OCoLC)1226679206  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.D6 -- R79 1999eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a070.1/81 aRussell, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExperimental Ethnography :bThe Work of Film in the Age of Video /cCatherine Russell. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b56 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tI. INTRODUCTION TO EXPERIMENTAL ETHNOGRAPHY -- t1. Another Look -- t2. Surrealist Ethnography -- tII. DOCUMENTARY BEFORE DOCUMENTARY -- t3. The Body as the Main Attraction -- t4. Ethnotopias of Early Cinema -- t5. Playing Primitive -- tIII. THE UNDISCIPLINED GAZE -- t6. Zoology, Pornography, Ethnography -- t7. Framing People: Structural Film Revisited -- tIV. OTHER REALITIES -- t8. Ecstatic Ethnography: Filming Possession Rituals -- t9. Archival Apocalypse: Found Footage as Ethnography -- tV. CONCLUSION -- t10. Autoethnography: Journeys of the Self -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExperimental film and ethnographic film have long been considered separate, autonomous practices on the margins of mainstream cinema. By exploring the interplay between the two forms, Catherine Russell throws new light on both the avant-garde and visual anthropology.Russell provides detailed analyses of more than thirty-five films and videos from the 1890s to the 1990s and discusses a wide range of film and videomakers, including Georges Méliès, Maya Deren, Peter Kubelka, Ray Birdwhistell, Jean Rouch, Su Friedrich, Bill Viola, Kidlat Tahimik, Margaret Mead, Tracey Moffatt, and Chantal Akerman. Arguing that video enables us to see film differently-not as a vanishing culture but as bodies inscripted in technology, Russell maps the slow fade from modernism to postmodern practices. Combining cultural critique with aesthetic analysis, she explores the dynamics of historical interruption, recovery, and reevaluation. As disciplinary boundaries dissolve, Russell contends, ethnography is a means of renewing the avant-gardism of "experimental" film, of mobilizing its play with language and form for historical ends. "Ethnography" likewise becomes an expansive term in which culture is represented from many different and fragmented perspectives.Original in both its choice of subject and its theoretical and methodologicalapproaches, Experimental Ethnography will appeal to visual anthropologists, as well as film scholars interested in experimental and documentary practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aGaze in motion pictures. 0aGazexPsychological aspects. 0aMotion pictures in ethnology. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822396680zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822396680423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822396680.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles